\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\b\f0\fs20 
\par Scribe Scroll
\par }{\f0\fs20 
Starting at 2nd level, a Mage can create scrolls from which he or another spellcaster can cast a scribed spell. You can create a scroll of any spell you know. Scribing a scroll takes one day. The purchase DC for the raw materials to scribe a scroll is 13 
+ the scroll\rquote s spell level + the scroll\rquote s caster level.
\par The Mage must also spend experience points to scribe a scroll. The XP cost is equal to the spell level \'a5 the caster level \'a5 the purchase DC of the raw materials.
\par Finally, the Mage makes a Craft (writin
g) check. The DC for the check is 10 + the spell level + the caster level of the scroll. If the check fails, the raw materials are used up but the XP are not spent. The Mage can try scribing the scroll again as soon as he purchases more raw materials.

\par Any scroll that stores a spell with a costly material component or an XP cost also carries a commensurate cost. In addition to the costs derived from the base price, you must expend the material component or pay the XP when scribing the scroll.
\par A scroll can be written on a sheet of paper or parchment, or it can be saved as a file on a computer or PDA.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Bonus Feats
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 
At 3rd, 6th, and 9th level, the Mage gets a bonus feat. The bonus feat must be selected from the following list, and the Mage must meet all the prerequisites of the feat to select it.
\par Attentive, Archaic Weapons Proficiency, Combat Expertise, Educated, Frightful Presence, Low Profile, Nimble, Studious.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Brew Potion
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 At 3rd level, a Mage can create potions, which carry spells within themselves.
\par The Mage can
 create a potion of any spell of 3rd level or lower that he knows. The spell must target a character or characters. Brewing a potion takes 24 hours. When the Mage creates a potion, he sets the caster level. The caster level must be sufficient to cast the 
spell in question and no higher than the Mage\rquote 
s class level. The caster level has an effect on the purchase DC of the raw materials to brew the potion, the skill check to create the potion, the experience point cost to brew the potion, and the DC of a savin
g throw (if applicable) to resist the effect of the potion.
\par The purchase DC for the raw materials to brew a potion is 15 + the potion\rquote s spell level + the potion\rquote s caster level.
\par The Mage must also spend experience points to brew a potion. The XP cost is equal to the spell level \'a5 the caster level \'a5 the purchase DC of the raw materials.
\par Finally, the Mage makes a Craft (chemical) check. The DC for the check is 10 + the spell level + the caster level of the potion. If the check fails, the raw materials are used
 up but the XP are not spent. The Mage can try brewing the potion again as soon as he purchases more raw materials.
\par When a Mage creates a potion, he makes any choices that he would normally make when casting the spell. Whoever drinks the potion is the target of the spell.
\par Any potion that stores a spell with a costly material component or an XP cost also carries a commensurate cost. In addition to the raw materials cost, the Mage must expend the material component or pay the XP when creating the potion.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Scribe Tattoo
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 At 4th level, a Mage can create tattoos on his body or someone else\rquote s. Tattoos function similarly to scrol
ls, and are created in the same way (see the scribe scroll ability), except that the pertinent skill is Craft (visual arts). See Chapter Ten: FX Abilities for more about tattoos.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Spell Mastery
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 At 5th and 8th level, a Mage gains the spell mastery ability. E
ach time, the Mage chooses a number of spells that he already knows equal to his Intelligence modifier. From that point on, the Mage can prepare these spells without referring to a spellbook. The Mage is so intimately familiar with these spells that he do
esn\rquote t need a spellbook to prepare them anymore.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Combat Casting
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 
At 7th level, a Mage becomes adept at casting spells during combat. He gets a +4 bonus on Concentration checks made to cast a spell while on the defensive.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Maximize Spell
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 At 10th level, a Mage l
earns to cast some of his spells to maximum effect. All variable, numeric effects of a maximized spell automatically achieve their maximum values. A maximized spell deals the most possible points of damage, affects the maximum number of targets, and so fo
rth, as appropriate. Saving throws and opposed checks are not affected. Spells without random variables are not affected. 
\par When a maximized spell is prepared, it is treated as a spell of three levels higher than the spell\rquote s actual level. Therefore, a Mage can only maximize 0-, 1st-, or 2nd-level spells\emdash 
a maximized 1st-level spell is treated as a 4th-level spell when you decide what spells the Mage will have available for the coming day, so it limits the number of other 4th-level spells the Mage can prepare. 
Likewise, a maximized 2nd-level spell is treated as a 5th-level spell.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel0\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs36\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0 ACOLYTE
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Requirements
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 To qualify to become an Acolyte, a character must fulfill the following criteria.
\par }{\b\f0\fs20 Base Attack Bonus: }{\f0\fs20 +2.
\par }{\b\f0\fs20 Skills:}{\f0\fs20  Knowledge (theology and philosophy) 6 ranks, Listen 6 ranks, Sense Motive 6 ranks.
\par Allegiance: At the time that the character receives her first level in the Acolyte advanced class, she must decide if her faith leans toward the positive energy or negative
 energy of the universe. This choice adds either the good (positive) or evil (negative) allegiance to the character, and determines how the Acolyte uses certain aspects of her faith.
\par }{\b\f0\fs20 Holy Symbol: }{\f0\fs20 When the character declares her allegiance, she must designa
te one of her personal possessions as a symbol of her dedication to her allegiance. This possession can be either an actual religious object or some other item of personal significance. This object is referred to as the Acolyte\rquote 
s holy symbol. It is typically of Tiny or Diminutive size, so that it can be easily held and manipulated in one hand, and its weight is negligible, so that it does not affect the Acolyte\rquote s carrying capacity.
\par An Acolyte needs her holy symbol in order to cast certain divine spells. It is also necessary for the Acolyte to be able to turn or rebuke undead (see below).
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Class Information
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 The following information pertains to the Acolyte advanced class.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Hit Die
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \f5\fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\fs20 The Acolyte gains 1d8 hit points per level. The character\rquote s Constitution modifier applies.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\nowidctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel2\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\up3\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\f0\up0 Action Points
